  "prompt": "How do they prove that light travels in wave?",
  "response": "Scientists have proven that light travels in waves through several key experiments and observations:\n\n1. Double-slit experiment\n- Light passing through two narrow slits creates an interference pattern\n- This pattern demonstrates wave-like behavior\n- Waves interfere with each other, creating alternating bright and dark bands\n\n2. Diffraction\n- Light bends around obstacles and spreads out\n- This behavior is characteristic of waves\n- Observed when light passes through small openings or around edges\n\n3. Polarization\n- Light waves can be oriented in specific directions\n- Polarizing filters can block or allow light based on wave orientation\n- Shows light has wave-like properties with oscillating electric and magnetic fields\n\n4. Electromagnetic spectrum\n- Different wavelengths correspond to different types of electromagnetic radiation\n- X-rays, radio waves, visible light are all demonstrated to have wave characteristics\n\n5. Quantum mechanics\n- Wave-particle duality shows light can behave as both a wave and a particle\n- Photons exhibit wave-like properties at quantum scales\n\n6. Spectroscopy\n- Light's wavelength determines its color and energy\n- Different wavelengths produce different spectral patterns\n\nThese experiments collectively provide strong evidence that light travels as a wave, with both wave and particle characteristics.",
